<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
<taxonomicName LSID="http://species-id.net/wiki/Apion_astragali" authority="Thunberg, 1815: 118" authorityName="Herbst" authorityYear="1797" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apion astragali" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astragali">Apion astragali Thunberg, 1815: 118</taxonomicName>
Fig. 3
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="original description">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Original description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">A. Astragali: caerulescens nitidus, elytris striatis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Habitat in Vestrogothia Sveciae.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Totus supra nitens, caerulescens; subtus magis niger magnitudine pediculi.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Elytra gibba, striata.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="94" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="material studied">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Material studied.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="94" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
I have received three specimens with red type labels as above, carrying the numbers 1206, 1289 and 1290. Only specimen nr. 1289 has an additional label reading 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Vestrog.”">&quot;Vestrog.&quot;</normalizedToken>
. This specimen, pinned high on a long pin with head, is 
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="94" start="start">a</pageBreakToken>
female 
<taxonomicName authority="Ehert, 1990" authorityName="Ehert" authorityYear="1990" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Pseudoprotapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudoprotapion astragali" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astragali">Pseudoprotapion astragali</taxonomicName>
(Paykull, 1800) and is here designated as lectotype. This allows establishment of the following new synonymy: 
<taxonomicName authority="Ehert, 1990" authorityName="Ehert" authorityYear="1990" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Pseudoprotapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudoprotapion astragali" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astragali">Pseudoprotapion astragali</taxonomicName>
(Paykull, 1800) = 
<taxonomicName authority="Herbst, 1797" authorityName="Herbst" authorityYear="1797" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apion astragali" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astragali">Apion astragali</taxonomicName>
Thunberg, 1815. Specimen 1206 is a male of the same species and is designated as paralectotype. However, specimen 1290 does not fit the original description and is not considered to represent a syntype, not being bright bluish as the others but dull bronze-black. It is a female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schilsky, 1901" authorityName="Schilsky" authorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Aspidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidapion radiolus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="radiolus">Aspidapion radiolus</taxonomicName>
(Marsham, 1802). 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Thunberg’s">Thunberg's</normalizedToken>
original species label of this specimen carries a question mark and the letter 
<normalizedToken originalValue="β">β</normalizedToken>
, in contrast with the other two, which carry the letter 
<normalizedToken originalValue="α">α</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
